You can get even nicer and more useful (due to generated assertion messages) with Sweet.js macros (<a href="https://github.com/andreypopp/sweet-assertions" rel="nofollow">https://github.com/andreypopp/sweet-assertions</a>)<p><pre><code>  describe &#x27;when the universe exists&#x27; {
    it &#x27;should be active&#x27; {
      universe.active should be true
    }
  }
</code></pre>
The pre-generated assertion messages means you get `universe.active should be true` in case of error which includes actual source of the expression.
